[[File:Jonathan Edwards olympics 2000.jpg|thumb|right|[[Triple jump]]er [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] was the first to win the award twice.]] The '''European Athlete of the Year Trophy''' is an [[Athlete of the Year|annual prize]] awarded to sportspeople participating in [[athletics (sport)|athletics]], including [[track and field]], [[road running]] and [[cross country running]] competitions. The election has been organised by the European governing body for the sport of athletics, the [[European Athletic Association]] (EAA), since [[1993 in sports|1993]].
Each year, a [[shortlist]] is created by selecting the top European athlete in each event, based upon performances at the year's major championships. Only in exceptional circumstances will more than one athlete be shortlisted per event. Athletes who have served a [[Use of performance-enhancing drugs in sport|doping ban]] of two years or more are ineligible.<ref>[http://www.european-athletics.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7754&Itemid=2 European Athlete of the Year Award nominations for 2009]. [[European Athletics]] (2009-09-14). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref> Via the EAA website, fans, media and members of the EAA federations are allowed to vote for five male and five female athletes on the list, with athletes receiving one to five points based on their ranking. A panel of experts also cast their votes. The votes of each of the four groups comprises 25% of the athletes' total scores, and the male and female athletes with the highest combined points totals win.<ref>[http://google.com/search?q=cache:siJDvGCB6LAJ:www.european-athletics.com/index.php%3Foption%3Dcom_content%26task%3Dview%26id%3D5561%26Itemid%3D2+European+Athletics+Rising+Star&cd=6&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk&client=firefox-a European Athletics Rising Star Awards nominations for 2009 ]. [[European Athletics]] (2009). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref><ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=54539.html Idowu and Domínguez win European Athlete of the Year Awards]. [[IAAF]] (2009-10-02). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref>
The '''European Athletics Rising Star of the Year Award''' was inaugurated in 2007. The award, open to athletes under 23 years of age, was created as a way of acknowledging young competitors' achievements on their way to becoming senior athletes.<ref>[http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/september-2007/artcile-36/ Jessica Ennis wins European Athletics Rising Star Award]. [[UK Athletics]] (2007-09-26). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref>
[[Waterford Crystal]] sponsored the event from 2002–2008 and [[:it:Mondo (azienda)|Mondo]], a manufacturer of [[track and field]] equipment and facilities, sponsored the 2009 presentation.<ref>[http://www.european-athletics.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7724&Itemid=159 MONDO becomes presenting partner for European Athletics Awards Night] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091006095727/http://www.european-athletics.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7724&Itemid=159 |date=2009-10-06 }}. [[European Athletics]] (2009-09-01). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref><ref>[http://www.european-athletics.org/files/publications/update024.pdf Update EAA – Newsletter of the European Athletics Association]. [[European Athletics]] (October 2002). Retrieved on 2009-10-02.</ref>
[[Mo Farah]] of Great Britain is the only athlete, male or female, to win the main award three times. Czech javelin legend [[Jan Železný]], British triple jumper [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] and his Swedish rival [[Christian Olsen]] have won the men's award twice, while Sweden's heptathlete [[Carolina Klüft]], the Russian pole vaulter [[Yelena Isinbayeva]], Croat high jumper [[Blanka Vlasic]] and Dutch sprinter [[Dafne Schippers]] have won the women's award twice each. Two athletes have completed the double of the Rising Star award, followed by the senior award; sprinter [[Christophe Lemaitre]] of France, and Great Britain's Olympic and World champion heptathlete [[Jessica Ennis-Hill]].
