{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = The Grove, Gore Court | country = England | image = Gore Court Cricket Club - geograph.org.uk - 676238.jpg | caption = Gore Court Cricket Club Located within Grove Park, Key Street, Sittingbourne | location = [[Sittingbourne]], [[Kent]] | coordinates = {{Coord|51.405|N|0.018|E|type:landmark|display=title, inline}} | establishment = 1860 | home club = Gore Court Cricket Club | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1929–present | club1 = Gore Court Cricket Club | year2 = 1930–1997 | club2 = [[Kent County Cricket Club]] Second XI | date = 6 September | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737.html CricketArchive }}
'''The Grove, Gore Court''' is a sports ground in [[Sittingbourne]] in [[Kent]]. It is used for [[cricket]] and [[field hockey|hockey]] by Gore Court. The ground is to the west of the centre of Sittingbourne, along the [[A2 road (Great Britain)|main A2 London road]].
The first recorded cricket match on the ground was in 1860, when the Gentlemen of Kent played the Gentlemen of Berkshire.<ref name=camisc>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737_misc.html Other matches played on The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref> The [[Kent County Cricket Club]] Second XI first used the ground in the 1930 [[Minor Counties Championship]] against [[Wiltshire County Cricket Club|Wiltshire]]. From 1930 to 1997, the ground held a combined total of 38 Second XI fixtures for the Kent Second XI in the Minor Counties Championship, [[Second XI Championship]] and Second XI Trophy.<ref name=camcc>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737_minc.html Minor Counties Championship Matches played on The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref><ref name=caseconds>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737_sec.html Second XI Championship Matches played on The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref><ref name=catrophy>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737_set.html Second XI Trophy Matches played on The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref>
In the [[1973 Women's Cricket World Cup]], the ground held a single match between [[Young England women's cricket team|Young England women]] and [[Jamaican women's cricket team|Jamaica women]].<ref name=cawomen>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737_wo.html Women's One-Day International Matches played on The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref>
The ground is the home venue of Gore Court Cricket Club who play in the [[Kent Cricket League]] and have used the ground since 1929.<ref name=ca>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/737.html The Grove, Sittingbourne], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref><ref>[http://gorecourt.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp Gore Court Cricket Club]. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref> The club's previous ground was on Bell Road in the centre of the town.<ref name=history>[http://www.gorecourthc.co.uk/club-history Club history], Gore Court Hockey Club. Retrieved 2017-12-17.</ref> Gore Court Hockey Club has shared the ground since 1930 and formally merged with the cricket club after the [[Second World War]]. The ground was used for Hockey County Championship matches between 1967 and the early 1980s. [[Jason Lee (field hockey)|Jason Lee]], who went on to coach the England and Great Britain men's teams and the England women's team, played for the club and represented Great Britain at the 1992 and 1996 Olympic Games.<ref name=history />
